05":"1305","1313":"1313","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1309":"1309","1306":"1306","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shelton, Norfolk, England":"Shelton, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shelton,Norfolk,England":"Shelton, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1280–1309":"1280–1309","1280–1350":"1280–1350","–1333":"–1333","1292–1333":"1292–1333","1305–1334":"1305–1334","1306–1333":"1306–1333","1313–1360":"1313–1360","about 1292":"about 1292","1305 2nd son":"February 1305","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1292":"1292","1280":"1280","Abt 1306":"about 1306","1305":"1305","1313":"1313","1334":"1334","1333":"1333","1309":"1309","1306":"1306","Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Shelton, Norfolk, England":"Shelton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Shelton,Norfolk,England":"Shelton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Powys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Powis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Powis","meanings":["Welsh (now mainly West Midlands of England): habitational name from the region of Powis in mid Wales (from Old Welsh <i>powes</i> ‘country dwellers’)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margaret  Maud Powys was born in 1280. She had at least 4 sons with John De Shelton. She died in 1309, in Shelton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1280–1309":"1280–1309","1280–1350